did.abstract: The papers consist of correspondence, letterbooks, order books, signal logs, and related naval and Admiralty papers that document aspects of Sir John Orde's naval career, primarily during the Napoleonic Wars. The collection provides substantial information related to Orde's bitter disputes with Admiral of the Fleet John Jervis, Lord St. Vincent; his rivalry with Horatio Nelson; and his professional frustration with the workings of the Admiralty Board and its bureaucracy. The collection also contains information on Orde's tenure as governor of Dominica and his suppression of mutinies at Plymouth and on board the Princess Royal. In addition to Lord St. Vincent and Horatio Nelson, correspondents include Baron Gambier, Sir John Duckworth, Sir Evan Nepean, Viscount Melville, and other contemporary naval and political figures.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Lot 119 from Christie's sale of Wednesday, 7 June 2006. The Sir John Orde Papers were purchased from Bernard Quaritch, Ltd. on the James Marshall and Marie-Louise Osborn Fund, 2006.

bioghist.head: Sir John Orde, 1751-1824
bioghist.p: Sir John Orde, first baronet, naval officer and politician, was born in Morpeth, England in 1751, the youngest son of John Orde (circa 1704-circa 1786) and the brother of Thomas Orde-Powlett, first Lord Bolton. Orde entered the navy in 1766; in 1773 he was promoted to lieutenant; and, during the American War of Independence, he was promoted to captain and took part in the reduction of Charlestown and the capture of several American ships. In 1781 he married Margaret Emma (1759-1790), daughter of Richard Stevens of Charlestown.

After the war, Orde was appointed governor of Dominica, where he governed successfully enough to be awarded a baronetcy in 1790; but when war broke out with France in 1793, Orde returned to the navy. Promoted to Rear Admiral in 1795, he served in the Mediterranean Fleet under John Jervis, Earl St. Vincent. However, a complaint that St. Vincent wrongly attributed to Orde sparked an acrimonious dispute between them, resulting in St. Vincent's command that Orde return to England; Orde's request that St. Vincent be court-martialed; his frustrated attempts to challenge St. Vincent to a duel; and pamphlets that Orde circulated privately defending his actions.

In 1804, having been promoted to Vice Admiral several years earlier, he commanded a successful blockade of Cadiz on Spain's entry into the war. Following complaints by Horatio Nelson, however, that Orde's blockade restricted his own opportunities to obtain prize money, Orde requested to return to England despite the ongoing war, occasioning another scandal.

In 1805 Orde was promoted to Admiral of the Blue, in 1809 to Admiral of the White, and in 1814 to Admiral of the Red. From 1807 to 1812 he served as Member of Parliament for Yarmouth. He died in 1824 after a long illness and was buried in Hanwell, Middlesex. His second wife, Jane (circa 1773-1829), daughter of John Frere, died in 1829; their son, John Powlett Orde, inherited the baronetcy on his father's death.
For further information, see Orde's entry in the Oxford Dictionary of National Biography.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Orde Papers consist of correspondence, letterbooks, order books, signal logs, and related naval and Admiralty papers that document aspects of Sir John Orde's naval career, primarily during the Napoleonic Wars. The papers span the dates 1789-1878, but the bulk of the material dates from between 1796 and 1805, and provides substantial information related to Orde's bitter disputes with the Admiral of the Fleet John Jervis, Lord St. Vincent; his rivalry with Horatio Nelson; and his career frustration with the entire Admiralty Board. The collection also contains information on his tenure as governor of Dominica and his suppression of mutinies at Plymouth and on the Princess Royal. The Orde Papers offer valuable insight into the Royal Navy's organization and actions during a crucial period of the Napoleonic Wars, as well as into the often conflicting professional agendas of the individual officers under its command.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is organized into four series: I. Correspondence; II. Letterbooks, Order Books, and Orders; III. Signal Books and Logs; and IV. Admiralty Papers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The bulk of Orde's correspondence consists of responses from naval officers, politicians, and other public figures to Orde's 1798 pamphlet describing his feud with Admiral St.Vincent. Correspondents on this subject include Alexander Hood,Viscount Bridport; John Pitt, Earl of Chatham; Richard Carr, Sir Glyn; Charles Lennox, Duke of Richmond and Lennox; and Richard Creyke. Many correspondents mention their prior knowledge of the dispute from newspaper accounts. In addition, the collection includes an official letter from Sir Evan Nepean to Admiral St. Vincent informing him of the King's command that he refuse any challenge to a duel from Orde.

The remaining correspondence primarily concerns Orde's other naval and political activities, especially in relation to his dissatisfaction with aspects of his naval career. An official letter by William, Baron Grenville in 1790 addresses colonial complaints against Orde during his governorship of Dominica. Several letters by James, Baron Gambier commend Orde's handling of the 1797 mutiny at Plymouth. The correspondence also includes numerous letters from St. Vincent himself, consisting of both official Admiralty correspondence with Orde and personal letters discussing military tactics. Other letters from St. Vincent admonish Orde for his dissatisfaction with Horatio Nelson's appointment as commander of a detached squadron to pursue Napoleon; order Orde to return to England in the Blenheim in 1798; and trace the growth of their quarrel. Several 1799 letters, including those by Sir William Parker and George Purvis, discuss the controversy over the division of the Nile Prize money.

The collection also contains several letters and drafts by Orde himself, including copies of notes to his wife written from the Princess Royal in 1798, which comment on his growing disagreement with St. Vincent. Copies of correspondence between Orde and Nelson detail Nelson's response to Orde's pamphlet and his defense of the Admiralty's decision to favor him with the Mediterranean command. Finally, a letter to Henry Dundas, Viscount Melville in 1805 discusses Orde's blockade at Cadiz and Nelson's complaints concerning it, as well as Orde's request to be allowed to resign from his command.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series II consists primarily of orders and other correspondence from the Admiralty Office to Orde and from Orde to his subordinates, dated between 1794-1805; and Orde's business papers, dated between 1799 and 1817.

Almost all of the letterbooks and order books contain both orders to Orde, and, dos-a-dos, Orde's responses or subsequent commands to his own subordinates. These books record naval commands at Gibraltar and Lisbon; positions of enemy ships, captures of ships, and details of prizes; personnel changes; and negotiations regarding the exchange of prisoners of war. Orde's letters are frequently of an administrative nature, requesting provisions and providing surveys of stores, as well as asking for updates on the hospital at Gibraltar. A significant portion of the correspondence refers to command of the Princess Royal, particularly supression of a planned mutiny in support of the Irish Rebellion of 1798.

This series also contains the official documents appointing Orde to Commander-in-Chief in 1804 and Admiral of the Red in 1814; instructions and regulations regarding flags and signals; diagrams and lists of battle positions; and a pamphlet of regulations governing behavior, dress, and duties on board ships under Orde's command. Additionally, numerous documents are devoted to recording the details of the vessels captured by Orde, including ships' names; numbers of men, tons, and guns on board; their origins and destinations; and their cargoes. Other documents concern the prize money from such captures, including a list of expected proceeds from detained vessels and an account of shares paid to various members of his squadron.
Financial papers include accounts relating to the Audit Office investigation of the charges that he continued to hold public monies from Dominica after his term as governor had ended.
Finally, this series contains two copies of Orde's defense of his request to be called home from Cadiz in 1805.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The series consists of chronologically arranged signal books and logs, dated between 1799-1806. These are primarily printed instructions, many with handwritten annotations as well as colored illustrations and diagrams of battle formations as dictated by signal flags. The collection also includes two signal logs for HMS Glory.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series IV, Admiralty Papers ,consists primarily of naval materials peripheral to Orde.The series also contains two printed pamphlets defending Orde's actions in his feud with St. Vincent. Both pamphlets include copies of correspondence and are annotated in Orde's hand; the pamphlet dated 1802 also includes one page, copied in Orde's hand and bound in, of correspondence with St. Vincent.
